															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/scorpion451" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1918720); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1918720&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164185" alt="Scorpion451" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1918720)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/scorpion451" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1918720); return false;" >Scorpion451</a></span> <span class="odate time_1525964423 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">10 May 2018 15:00</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3796201">
									

<p>Not to mention smithing is one of those art-sciences where things get lost and rediscovered over and over. The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sword_of_Goujian">Sword of Goujian</a><sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-807259-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-807259-1')">1</a></sup>is a good example- a bronze sword found in 1965 during the excavation of a ~2500 year old submerged tomb, still razor-sharp and shiny.</p>
<p>Took modern metal analysis to figure the thing out: Its still not 100% clear how the process worked (there's several theories), but apparently some unknown cadre of metallurgical geniuses in ancient China figured out how to marry a core of high-copper bronze to an edge of high-tin bronze, and then infuse the surface metal with sulfur to make it virtually immune to corrosion without screwing up the existing weld or the properties of the edge and core.</p>
<p>It's still a bronze sword with all the weaknesses that entails, but in terms of common technology at the time it was forged, this thing might as well have been made of nanobots. (And it's still a pretty darn impressive bit of smithing by today's standards.)</p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-807259-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-807259-1')">1</a>. And other, more recently discovered swords forged using the same techniques</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
